    <p class="text-gray-700">Italian Sangiovese or Chianti Classico are ideal matches for pepperoni pizza because their bright acidity cuts through the oil while their earthy notes complement the spiced meat. The wine's tannins also help cleanse your palate between the salty, fatty bites. For a budget-friendly option, try a Montepulciano d'Abruzzo, which offers similar characteristics at a lower price point.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is wine with pizza good for beginners who don't usually drink wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pizza is actually an excellent introduction to wine for beginners because the food's bold flavors make wine more approachable and less intimidating. Start with easy-drinking options like Lambrusco (slightly sparkling Italian red) or a light Pinot Grigio, which complement pizza without overwhelming novice palates. The casual nature of pizza dining removes the formality that often intimidates wine newcomers.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for pizza night?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing overly heavy, tannic wines like Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo, which can taste bitter against tomato sauce's acidity. Another frequent error is serving wine too warm, which amplifies alcohol and makes the pairing feel heavy and unbalanced. Instead, opt for medium-bodied wines with good acidity and serve them properly chilled.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good non-alcoholic alternatives that pair as well as wine with pizza?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling grape juice or non-alcoholic sparkling wine can provide similar palate-cleansing effects as traditional wine pairings. Italian sodas like San Pellegrino Limonata offer bright acidity that cuts through cheese and grease effectively. For the closest wine-like experience, try non-alcoholic reds from producers like Fre or Ariel, which maintain some of the complexity that makes wine such a natural pizza partner.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How much should I expect to spend on a good pizza wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Excellent pizza wines can be found in the $8-15 range, with Italian options like Montepulciano d'Abruzzo or basic Chianti offering outstanding value. Spending $20-30 opens up premium Chianti Classico or quality Sangiovese that will elevate your pizza experience significantly. The key is choosing wines with good acidity over expensive, prestigious bottles that may not complement the casual meal as well.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I use leftover pizza wine for cooking the next day?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely! Pizza wines like Chianti or Sangiovese are perfect for cooking Italian dishes within 2-3 days of opening. Use them in tomato-based pasta sauces, risottos, or braising liquids where their acidity and fruit flavors will enhance the dish. Store opened bottles in the refrigerator with a wine stopper to maintain freshness for culinary use.</p>
